8.02	Ayuba_Suleiman_Diallo	Ayuba Suleiman Diallo	Ayuba Suleiman Diallo (1701â€“1773), also known as Job ben Solomon, was a famous enslaved Muslim who was a victim of the Atlantic slave trade. Born in Bondu, Senegal West Africa, Ayuba's memoirs were published as one of the earliest slave narratives, that is, a first-person account of the slave trade, in Thomas Bluett's Some Memories of the Life of Job, the Son of the Solomon High Priest of Boonda in Africa; Who was enslaved about two Years in Maryland; and afterwards being brought to England, was set free, and sent to his native Land in the Year 1734. However, this version is not a first-person account.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/William_Hoare_of_Bath_-_Portrait_of_Ayuba_Suleiman_Diallo%2C_%281701-1773%29.jpg/220px-William_Hoare_of_Bath_-_Portrait_of_Ayuba_Suleiman_Diallo%2C_%281701-1773%29.jpg
